A067368.name: a(n) is the smallest positive even integer that cannot be expressed as the product of two or three previous terms (not necessarily distinct).
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = a(n-1) + 2 if (n = 2a(k) + k + 1) or (n = 2a(k) + k) for some k, otherwise a(n) = a(n-1) + 4. This has been confirmed for several hundred terms.

The above conjecture is correct because there are 2*(a(k+1)-a(k)) terms that are not divisible by 4 in the k-th interval which are determined by terms that are divisible by 4. For example, there are 2*(a(2)-a(1)) = 2*(6-2) = 8 terms between a(5) = 16 and a(14) = 48 because numbers of the form 2*s are always terms where s is an odd number. So first differences of a(n) determine the corresponding intervals and the formula above always holds. - _Altug Alkan_, Sep 24 2018

A067370.name: The weight of the periphery of the alternating group, denoted v(P_N).

A067392.name: Sum of numbers <= n which have common prime factors with n.
formula: a(p) = p where p is a prime; a(2^k) = 2^(k-1)*{2^(k-1) + 1).

A067393.name: Number of nonprimes among the numbers in {1,2,3,...,n!} which are relatively prime to n!.

formula: Let k=floor(log3(n)), i.e., 3^k<=n<3^(k+1): if (3/2)*3^k<n<(5/2)*3^k then a(n)=a(n-3^k)+1, if n=3*3^k-1 then a(n)=a(n-3^k)-1=0, otherwise a(n)=a(n-3^k) [starting with a(0)=0, so a(3^k)=0].

A067399.name: Number of divisors of n in OR-numbral arithmetic.

A067400.name: Non-uniquely factorizable OR-numbrals, i.e., numbrals for which there exist more than one different factorizations into irreducible factors (modulo order).

A067417.name: Triangle with columns built from certain power sequences.

A067418.name: Triangle A067330 with rows read backwards.
formula: G.f. for column m=0, 1, ...: (x^m)*(F(m+1)+F(m)*x)/(1-x-x^2)^2, with F(m) := A000045(m) (Fibonacci).

A067419.name: Fourth column of triangle A067417.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A134309(n,k)*6^k = Sum_{k=0..n} A055372(n,k)*5^k. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 04 2012

A067425.name: Triangle with columns built from certain power sequences.

A067431.name: Convolution of Fibonacci F(n+1), n>=0, with F(n+8), n>=0.

A067432.name: Number of ways to represent the n-th prime in form p*q+p+q, where p and q are primes (see A066938).

A067433.name: Triangle in which row n gives trajectory of n under the map k -> k/3 if k is divisible by 3, otherwise k -> next multiple of 3, stopping when reaching 1 (the initial term n is not included).

A067434.name: Number of distinct prime factors in binomial(2*n,n).
formula: a(n) ~ kn/log n, with k = log 4. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 25 2013

A067435.name: a(n) is the sum of all the remainders when n-th odd number is divided by odd numbers < 2n-1.

A067436.name: a(n) = sum of all the remainders when n-th even number is divided by even numbers < 2n.

A067437.name: Number of distinct prime factors in binomial(2*n,n)+1.

A067438.name: Number of distinct prime factors in floor((4/3)^n).

A067439.name: a(n) = sum of all the remainders when n is divided by positive integers less than and coprime to n.

A067440.name: Sum(i(n)), where i(n) is the smallest integer with i(n)^m=n for some m.

A067441.name: Number of distinct prime factors in floor((5/4)^n).

A067442.name: a(1) = 1 and then smallest nontrivial n-th power starting with 1.

A067448.name: Smallest n-th power whose decimal expansion starts with 7.

A067451.name: Numbers such that the geometric and arithmetic mean of their decimal digits are integers.

A067452.name: Numbers, not composed of the same digits, such that the geometric and arithmetic means of their decimal digits are integers.

A067453.name: a(n) = binomial(a,b) where a>=b and one of a and b is the product of the nonzero decimal digits of n and the other is the sum of the decimal digits of n.

A067454.name: Binomial(a,b) where a = n! and b = sum of first n natural numbers.

A067455.name: n! divided by the product of the decimal digits of n.

A067456.name: Floor( sqrt( sum of the decimal digits of n squared)).

A067457.name: Smallest n-th power starting with n.

A067458.name: Sum of remainders when n is divided by its nonzero digits.

A067459.name: Sum of the remainders when n^2 is divided by squares less than n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n-1} (n^2 mod k^2). [From _Robert Israel_, Jan 07 2021 Maple program.]

A067463.name: Primes p such that p+sigma(p+1) is prime.

A067464.name: Primes p such that sigma(p-1)+sigma(p+1) is prime.

A067465.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n^2+1) is a perfect square.

A067466.name: Primes p such that p-1 has 2 distinct prime factors.

A067467.name: Primes p such that p-1 has 3 distinct prime factors.

A067468.name: Numbers n such that 7 is the first digit of 7^n.

A067469.name: Numbers k such that 2 is the first digit of 2^k.

A067472.name: Smallest n-digit square starting with 2.
formula: a(n) = ceiling(sqrt(2*10^(n-1)))^2, n>1. - _Rick L. Shepherd_, Feb 14 2002

A067473.name: Smallest n-digit square starting with 3.
formula: a(n) = ceiling(sqrt(3*10^(n-1)))^2, n>1. - _Rick L. Shepherd_, Feb 14 2002

A067475.name: Smallest n-digit square starting with 5.
formula: a(n) = ceiling(sqrt(5*10^(n-1)))^2, n>2. - _Rick L. Shepherd_, Feb 18 2002

A067476.name: Smallest n-digit square starting with 6.
formula: a(n) = ceiling(sqrt(6*10^(n-1)))^2, n>1. - _Rick L. Shepherd_, Feb 18 2002

A067477.name: Smallest n-digit square starting with 7.
formula: a(n) = ceiling(sqrt(7*10^(n-1)))^2, n>2. - _Rick L. Shepherd_, Feb 18 2002

A067479.name: Smallest n-digit square starting with 9, or 0 if no such number exists.

A067490.name: Powers of 4 with initial digit 1.
formula: a(n+1)/a(n) is in {16, 64, 1024}, so 16^n <= a(n+1) < 1024^n. Asymptotically, the exponent should be 100; I can prove that 99^n << a(n) << 101^n. [_Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jan 19 2012]

A067497.name: Smallest power of 2 with n+1 digits (n>=0). Also numbers k such that 1 is the first digit of 2^k.

A067513.name: Number of divisors d of n such that d+1 is prime.

A067515.name: Fibonacci numbers with index = digit sum.

A067516.name: Fibonacci numbers starting with a Fibonacci number of at least two digits.

A067522.name: Smallest prime with sum of digits = 2^n.

A067523.name: The smallest prime with a possible given digit sum.
formula: a(n) = min(prime(i): A007605(i) = A133223(i)). - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 06 2018

A067524.name: Smallest composite number with digit sum n.

A067525.name: Define I(n) = number obtained by incrementing each digit from 0 to 8 of n by 1. A '9' is replaced by a '0'. Sequence gives digitriangular numbers n*I(n)/2.

A067526.name: Numbers n such that n - 2^k is a prime or 1 for all k satisfying 0 < k, 2^k < n.

A067527.name: n - 3^k is a prime for all k > 0 such that 3^k < n.

A067528.name: Numbers n such that n - 4^k is a prime or 1 for all k > 0 and n > 4^k.

A067529.name: n - 5^k is a prime for all k > 0 and n > 5^k.

A067530.name: n - k! is a prime or 1 for all k > 1 and n > k!.

A067531.name: Numbers n such that n - number of divisors of n is a prime.

A067532.name: Numbers n such that n + number of divisors is a prime.

A067533.name: Numbers k such that both k - tau(k) and k + tau(k) are prime where tau(k) = A000005(k).

A067534.name: a(n) = 4^n * sum_{i=1,n} i^4/4^i.
formula: Recurrence equation: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) + n^4. See A047520 and A066999.

A067536.name: Numbers k such that phi(k*(k+1)*(k+2)/3)/phi(k) is not an integer where phi(k) is the Euler totient function A000010(k).

A067538.name: Number of partitions of n in which the number of parts divides n.

A067539.name: Number of partitions of n in which, if the number of parts is k, the product of the parts is the k-th power of some positive integer.

A067540.name: Number of partitions of n in which the sum of reciprocal of parts divides number of parts.
formula: a(n)=#{n=p_1+p_2+...+p_r : r/sum_{i=1..r} 1/p_i is an integer} where n=p_1+p_2+...+p_r runs over all partitions of n. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Mar 24 2013
a(n) <= A058360(n) <= A000041(n). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 15 2020

A067541.name: phi(n*(n+1)/2)/phi(n) where phi is the Euler totient function A000010(n).
formula: Let n = 2^k*m, GCD(m, 2) = 1.  Then a(n) = phi((n + 1)/2) if k = 0, phi(n + 1) if k = 1 and (phi(n + 1))/2 if k > 1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Feb 06 2002

A067542.name: Primes p such that p+5==0 (mod phi(p+5)).

A067543.name: Numbers n such that phi(n*(n+1)*(n+2)*(n+3)/4!)/phi(n*(n+1)*(n+2)/3!) is not an integer where phi(n)=A000010(n) is the Euler totient function.

A067544.name: Numbers n such that phi(n*(n+1)*(n+2)/6)/phi(n*(n+1)/2) is not an integer where phi(n)=A000010(n) is the Euler totient function.

A067545.name: Determinant of an n X n matrix whose diagonal are the first n composite numbers and all other elements are 1's.

A067546.name: Determinant of an n X n matrix whose diagonal are the first n nonprime numbers and all other elements are 1's.

A067547.name: Number of divisors of n equals the average of distinct prime factors of n.

A067548.name: Least k > n such that gcd(prime(n)+k, n+prime(k)) > 1.

A067549.name: Determinant of n X n matrix whose diagonal are the first n primes and all other elements are 1's.

A067551.name: Determinant of an n X n matrix whose diagonal are the first n Primes of alternating sign and all other elements are 1's.

A067552.name: a(n) = SumOfDigits(n)^2 - SumOfDigits(n^2), where SumOfDigits = A007953.

A067553.name: Sum of products of terms in all partitions of n into odd parts.

A067554.name: Number of partitions of n in which the product of parts is a power of n.

A067555.name: Smallest number m>1 such that the product of the parts in some partition of m is equal to m^n.
formula: Let the prime factorization of m be product{p_i}. a(n)=m is the least number such that m >= sum{p_i} * n . - Fung Cheok Yin (cheokyin_restart(AT)yahoo.com.hk), Aug 16 2006

A067556.name: Terms in the decimal expansion of 1/(7*2^n) before the block of decimals 142857 (the period of 1/7) appears.

A067557.name: Primes p such that p-5 == 0 (mod phi(p-5)).

A067558.name: Sum of squares of proper divisors of n.

A067559.name: Numbers n such that floor(Pi*n^2) is prime.

A067560.name: Determinant of n X n matrix whose rows are cyclic permutations of 1..n-th nonprime (A018252).

A067561.name: Radii n of circles with integer radius that can approximately be squared integrally: the floor or ceiling of Pi*n^2 is an integer square.

A067562.name: Odd values of k such that phi(k)! divides phi(k!) where phi(k) = A000010(k).

A067563.name: Product of n-th prime number and n-th composite number.

A067564.name: Numbers n such that determinant[{{n, phi(n), sigma(n)}, {n+1, phi(n+1), sigma(n+1)}, {n+2, phi(n+2), sigma(n+2)}] is a nonnegative cube.

A067565.name: Inverse of R. L. Graham's sequence (A006255), or zero if and only if n is a prime.

A067566.name: Smallest k such that k = n*A001414(k) (or 0 if no such k exists), where A001414(k) is the integer log of k, i.e., Sum p_i*e_i if the prime factorization of k is Product p_i^e_i.

A067567.name: Odd numbers with an odd number of partitions.

A067568.name: Numbers n such that A000009(n) divides A022629(n).

A067569.name: Numbers n such that A000041(n) divides A006906(n).

A067570.name: Numbers n such that A000009(n) divides A067553(n).

A067571.name: Numbers n such that determinant[{{n,phi(n)},{n+1,phi(n+1)}}]is a perfect square.

A067572.name: Numbers n such that determinant[{{n, sigma(n)}, {n+1, sigma(n+1)}}] is a perfect square.

A067573.name: Numbers such that Sigma(Phi(k))/Sigma(k) > Sigma(Phi(j))/Sigma(j) for all k > j.

A067574.name: Array T(i,j) read by antidiagonals, where T(i,j) is the concatenation of i and j (1<=i, 1<=j).

A067575.name: Numbers n such that n divides phi(n)*bigomega(n).
formula: If n=4^k k>=0 n is in the sequence

A067576.name: Array T(i,j) read by antidiagonals, where T(i,j) is the j-th term whose binary expansion has i 1's.

A067578.name: a(n) = Product_{i=1..n} phi(i) * Sum_{i=1..n} 1/phi(i) where phi is the Euler totient function A000010(n).

A067579.name: Conjectured values of a(n) defined by: a(n) = first prime appearing in the orbit n, f(n), f(f(n)),...., if it exists; = 0 otherwise, where f(n) = n + sigma(n).

A067581.name: a(n) = smallest integer not yet in the sequence with no digits in common with a(n-1), a(0)=0.

A067582.name: Nonprime values of n such that bigomega(n)^omega(n)=omega(n)^bigomega(n) where bigomega(n) is the number of prime factors of n (counted with multiplicity) and omega(n) the number of distinct prime factors of n.

A067583.name: Integers of the form phi(n^n)/phi(n)^n where phi is the Euler totient function A000010(n).
formula: If A007694(n)==0 (mod 3) (or equivalently if A007694(n) = 2^u*3^v with u, v >=1) then a(n) =3^(A007694(n) -1); if A007694(n)=2^u a(n)=2^(A007694(n) -1). Remark : if n=3^v phi(n^n)/phi(n)^n=1/2^(n-1)

A067584.name: Product of divisors of n-th perfect number.
formula: a(n) = A000396(n)^A000043(n) whenever A000396(n) is an even perfect number. (Proof of the existence of odd perfect numbers is a well-known open problem.) A000043(n) is a Mersenne prime.

A067585.name: Binary representation of a(n) is obtained thus: replace every digit in the binary representation of n with "1" if the sum of its neighbors is 1 and with "0" otherwise.

A067586.name: Number of 0's in the binary expansion of A066884(n+1).

A067587.name: Inverse of A066884 considered as a permutation of the positive integers.
formula: Let w(n)=A000120(n) be the 'weight' of n; i.e. the number of 1's in the binary expansion of n. Let p(n)=A068076(n) be the number of positive integers < n with the same weight as n. Then a(n) = binomial(w(n)+p(n), 2) + p(n) + 1.

A067588.name: Total number of parts in all partitions of n into odd parts.
formula: G.f.: G(x)*H(x) where G(x) = Sum_{k>=1) x^(2*k-1)/(1-x^(2*k-1)) is g.f. for the number of odd divisors of n (cf. A001227) and H(x) = Product_{k>=1) (1+x^k) is g.f. for the number of partitions of n into odd parts (cf. A000009). Convolution of A001227 and A000009: Sum_{k=0..n} A001227(k)*A000009(n-k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Feb 04 2002
a(n) ~ 3^(1/4) * (2*gamma + log(48*n/Pi^2)) * exp(Pi*sqrt(n/3)) / (8*Pi*n^(1/4)), where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 25 2018

A067589.name: Numbers k such that A067588(k) is an odd number.
formula: The terms are exactly the odd pentagonal numbers; that is, they are all the odd numbers of the form k*(3*k-1)/2 where k is an integer. - _James A. Sellers_, Jun 09 2007

A067590.name: Number of partitions of n into odious numbers (A000069).
formula: Euler Transform of characteristic function of A000069.

A067591.name: Number of partitions of n into evil numbers (A001969).
formula: Euler Transform of characteristic function of A001969.

A067592.name: Number of partitions of n into Lucas parts (A000204(k) for k >= 1).

A067593.name: Number of partitions of n into Lucas parts (A000032).

A067594.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct lucky parts (A000959).

A067595.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct Lucas parts (A000032).
formula: G.f.: B(x) * (1 + x^2) where B(x) is the g.f. of A003263. [_Joerg Arndt_, Jul 14 2013]

A067596.name: Number of partitions of n into palindrome parts in base 2.

A067597.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct palindrome parts in base 2.

A067598.name: Decimal encoding of the prime factorization of n is a multiple of n.

A067599.name: Decimal encoding of the prime factorization of n: concatenation of prime factors and exponents.

A067600.name: Numbers n such that f(n) and f(f(n)) are prime, where f(k) = decimal encoding of the prime factorization of k.

A067601.name: a(n) is the number of inequivalent permutations of {0..2n-1}, such that the first differences (modulo 2n) are a permutation of {1..2n-1}.

A067603.name: Least k such that gcd(prime(k)+1, prime(k+1)+1) = 2n.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = least k such that A001223(k) = 2n and A000040(k) == -1 (mod 2n). - _Zak Seidov_, Aug 16 2015

A067604.name: Smallest prime p of two consecutive primes, p < q, such that gcd(p+1, q+1) = 2n.

A067605.name: Least k such that gcd(prime(k+1)-1, prime(k)-1) = 2n.

A067606.name: Primes p such that p+7==0 (mod phi(p+7)).

A067607.name: Number of pancake stacks requiring a maximum number of flips to order.

A067608.name: Number of structural alkanes with combinatorial diameter n.

A067609.name: Number of stereo alkanes with combinatorial diameter n.

A067610.name: Number of stereo alkanes not containing a certain forbidden substructure) with combinatorial diameter n.

A067611.name: Numbers of the form 6xy +- x +- y, where x, y are positive integers.

A067613.name: Triangular table of coefficients of the Hermite polynomials, divided by 2^floor(n/2).

A067614.name: floor(1/(sqrt(prime(n))-floor(sqrt(prime(n))))), where prime(n) is the n-th prime.

A067615.name: Terms in decimal expansion of 1/(17*2^n) before 5882352941176470 (the period with no leading zeros of 1/17) appears.

A067618.name: Number of self-conjugate partitions of n into prime parts.

A067619.name: Total number of parts in all self-conjugate partitions of n. Also, sum of largest parts of all self-conjugate partitions of n.
formula: Let F(q) = Product_{i >= 1} (1 + q^(2*i-1)). Then A(q) = Sum_{n >= 0} ( F(q) - Product_{i = 1..n} (1 + q^(2*i-1)) ).
It follows that the above sum A(q) satisfies -A(q-1) = 1 + q + 3*q^2 + 12*q^3 + 61*q^4 + ..., the g.f. for A158691, row-Fishburn matrices of size n. (End)

A067620.name: a(n) = p^e, where p and e are the rounded means of the prime factors p_i and the exponents e_i, respectively, in the factorization n = p_1^e_1 * ... * p_r^e_r of n into distinct primes p_i. Each mean is rounded to the nearest integer, rounding up if there's a choice.

A067621.name: Let t = coefficient of x^(2n+1) in expansion of sin(x)/(1-x^2); a(n)=denominator(t)-numerator(t).
formula: a(n) is the difference between denominator and numerator of sum(i=0, n, (-1)^i/(2i+1)!)

A067622.name: Consider the power series (x + 1)^(1/3) = 1 + x/3-x^2/9 + 5x^3/81 + ...; sequence gives numerators of coefficients.

A067623.name: Consider the power series (x+1)^(1/3)=1+x/3-x^2/9+5x^3/81+...; sequence gives denominators of coefficients.

A067624.name: a(n) = 2^(2*n)*(2*n)!.
formula: a(n) = A000165(2*n) where A000165(k) are the double factorial numbers 2^k*k!=(2k)!!. - Corrected by _Johannes W. Meijer_, Jul 05 2009

A067625.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) = phi(prime(n)+1).

A067626.name: a(n) = 2^(2n+1)*(2n+1)!.
formula: a(n) = A000165(2n+2) where A000165(k) are the double factorial numbers 2^k*k!=(2k)!!.

A067627.name: Triangle T(n,k) = number of conjugacy classes of partitions of n using only k types of piles, read by rows.

A067628.name: Minimal perimeter of polyiamond with n triangles.
formula: Let c(n) = ceiling(sqrt(6n)). Then a(n) is whichever of c(n) or c(n) + 1 has the same parity as n.
a(n) = 2*ceiling((n + sqrt(6*n))/2) - n (Harary and Harborth, 1976). - _Stefano Spezia_, Oct 02 2019

A067629.name: The average of the prime factors of n, rounded off to the nearest integer (rounding up if there's a choice), with each factor weighted according to its frequency of occurrence in the prime factorization.

A067630.name: Denominators in power series for cos(x)*cosh(x).

A067631.name: If n is composite then a(n) is the standard deviation of the prime factors of n, rounded off to the nearest integer (rounding up if there's a choice), with each factor counted according to its frequency of occurrence in the prime factorization. If n is 1 or prime then a(n)=0.

A067633.name: a(1) = 1; sequence of digits of a(n)^2 is a subsequence of the sequence of digits of a(n+1)^2.

A067634.name: a(1) = 1; string of digits of a(n)^2 is a substring of the string of digits of a(n+1)^2.

A067635.name: a(1) = 1; set of digits of a(n)^2 is a proper subset of the set of digits of a(n+1)^2.

A067636.name: Row 1 of table in A067640.
formula: a(n) = (2*n+2)!*(2*n+4)!/(n!*((n+2)!)^2*(n+3)!). [adapted to offset 0 by _Georg Fischer_, May 29 2021]
D-finite with recurrence: a(0) = 2, n*(n+2)*(n+3)*a(n) - 4*(n+1)*(2*n+1)*(2*n+3)*a(n-1) = 0 for n >= 1. - _Georg Fischer_, May 29 2021

A067640.name: Table T(n,k) giving number of two-legged knot diagrams with n >= 0 self-intersections and k >= 0 tangencies, read by antidiagonals.

A067644.name: Number of prime alternating tangles (or knots) of type Gamma_1 with two connected components.

A067645.name: Number of prime alternating tangles (or knots) of type Gamma_2 with two connected components.

A067646.name: Number of prime alternating tangles (or knots) with two connected components.

A067647.name: Number of knot diagrams of type 1PI with n crossings and two outgoing strings.

A067648.name: Number of knot diagrams of type 2PI with n crossings and two outgoing strings.

A067649.name: Numerators of power series for sqrt(1+x^2)/sqrt(1-x).

A067650.name: The start of a record-breaking run of consecutive integers with a number of prime factors not equal to 2.

A067651.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) = phi(prime(n)-1).

A067652.name: a(n) = H_n(2,3) = H_(n-1)(2,4) where H_n is the n-th hyperoperator.

A067653.name: Denominators of the coefficients in exp(x/(1-x)) power series.
formula: a(n) is the denominator of Sum_{i=1..n} binomial(n-1, i-1)/i!.

A067654.name: Numerators of the coefficients in power series expansion of exp(2x/(1-x)).
formula: a(n) is the numerator of Sum_{i=1..n} binomial(n-1, i-1)*2^i/i!.

A067655.name: Denominators of the coefficients in exp(2x/(1-x)) power series.
formula: a(n) is the denominator in Sum_{i=1..n} binomial(n-1, i-1)*2^i/i!.

A067656.name: Numbers n such that n!*B(2n) is an integer, where B(2n) are the Bernoulli numbers.
formula: Also numbers n>1 such that A000330[n] = Sum[k^2,{k,1,n}] = n(n+1)(2n+1)/6 divides A001044[n] = Product[k^2,{k,1,n}] = (n!)^2. Also numbers n>1 such that Numerator[n(n+1)(2n+1)/6 /(n!)^2] = 1. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Oct 05 2006

A067657.name: Prime values of A001008, the numerators of the Harmonic Numbers.

A067658.name: Odd integers k such that k = gcd(((k-1)/2)!+1, ((k-1)/2)^((k-1)/2)+1).

A067659.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts such that number of parts is odd.
formula: Expansion of (1-phi(-q))/(2*chi(-q)) in powers of q where phi(),chi() are Ramanujan theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 14 2006
G.f.: sum(n>=1, q^(2*n^2-n) / prod(k=1..2*n-1, 1-q^k ) ). [_Joerg Arndt_, Apr 01 2014]

A067660.name: Values of gcd(n!+1,2^n+1) not equal to 1 taking n in increasing order.
formula: If 2m+1 is prime and is in the sequence, 2m+1=gcd(m!+1, 2^m+1)

A067661.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts such that number of parts is even.
formula: Also we have the following identity involving 2 X 2 matrices:
Prod_{k >= 1} [ 1, q^k; q^k, 1 ] = [ A(q), B(q); B(q), A(q) ] [_Bill Gosper_, Jun 25 2005]
Expansion of (1 + phi(-x)) / (2*chi(-x)) in powers of x where phi(), chi() are Ramanujan theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 14 2006
Let B(x) denote the g.f. of A067659. Then
A(x) + B(x) is the g.f. of A000009.
1/(A(x) - B(x)) is the g.f. of A000041.
(A(x) + B(x))/(A(x) - B(x)) is the g.f. of A015128.
B(x)/(A(x) - B(x)) is the g.f. of A014968.
A(x)/(A(x^2) - B(x^2)) is the g.f. of A027187.
B(x)/(A(x^2) - B(x^2)) is the g.f. of A027193. (End)

A067662.name: Numbers n such that n^2 + 1 and n^4 + 1 are primes.

A067663.name: Sequence gives values of gcd(k!+1, k^k-1) when not equal to 1 in order of appearance.
formula: For some even k: gcd(k!+1, k^k-1) = k+1;
for some odd k: gcd(k!+1, k^k-1) = 2*k+1.

A067664.name: Numbers n such that n^2 + 1 and n^2 + n + 1 are primes.

A067665.name: The start of a record-setting run of consecutive integers i with distinct A001222(i).

A067666.name: Sum of squares of prime factors of n (counted with multiplicity).
formula: a(x*y) = a(x) + a(y); a(p^k) = k*p^2 for p prime.

A067670.name: Smallest prime of additive persistence n.
formula: a(2)=19, 19->10->1, so 2 summation steps are required to reach single-digit.

A067671.name: The prime factors of n are also prime factors of the decimal encoding (A067599) of the prime factorization of n.

A067675.name: Number of fixed convex polyominoes with n cells.

A067676.name: Number of fixed directed convex polyominoes with n cells.

A067677.name: Diagonals of the prime-composite array, B(m,n) which are zeros from the Second Borve Conjecture.

A067681.name: Diagonals and antidiagonals of the prime-composite array, B(m,n) which are zeros from the Third Borve Conjecture.

A067687.name: Expansion of 1/( 1 - x / Product_{n>=1} (1-x^n) ).
formula: O.g.f.: 1/(1-x*P(x)), P(x) - o.g.f. for number of partitions (A000041). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Aug 10 2010

a(n) ~ c / r^n, where r = 0.41960035259835647849877575356670002531808936312... is the root of the equation QPochhammer(r) = r and c = 0.3777957165566422058901624844315414446044096308877617181754... = Log[r]/(Log[(1 - r)*r] + QPolyGamma[1, r] - Log[r]*Derivative[0, 1][QPochhammer][r, r]). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 16 2017, updated Mar 31 2018

A067688.name: Composite n such that for some integer r, n equals the sum of the r-th powers of the prime factors of n (counted with multiplicity).

A067689.name: Inverse of determinant of n X n matrix whose (i,j)-th element is 1/(i+j).
formula: Equals A005249 * A000984. - Sharon Sela (sharonsela(AT)hotmail.com), Apr 18 2002
a(n) ~ A^3 * 2^(2*n^2 + n - 1/12) / (exp(1/4) * n^(1/4) * Pi^(n+1/2)), where A = A074962 = 1.2824271291... is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 01 2015

a(n) = Prod_{i=1..n}(Prod_{j=1..n} (i+j)) / Prod_{i=1..n}(Prod_{j=1..n-1} (i-j)^2),  n >= 1. See the Pólya and Szegő reference (special case) with the original Cauchy reference. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Apr 25 2016

A067690.name: gcd((2n)!+1, n!+1) when not equal to 1.

A067693.name: Minimum length of the self-conjugates partitions of n (0 if n=2; length of a partition is the number of parts).

A067694.name: Minimum number of distinct parts in a self-conjugate partition of n, or 0 if n=2.
formula: a(0)=a(2)=0; a(n^2)=1; a(4n+2)=3 for n>0; a(n)=2 in all other cases.

A067695.name: Smallest prime factor with minimal exponent in canonical prime factorization of n, a(1)=1.

A067696.name: Numbers k such that prime(k) == -1 (mod sigma(k)).

A067697.name: Numbers k such that prime(k) == 1 (mod sigma(k)).

A067698.name: Positive integers such that sigma(n) >= exp(gamma) * n * log(log(n)).

A067699.name: Number of comparisons made in a version of the sorting algorithm QuickSort for an array of size n with n identical elements.
formula: a(n) = 2*ceiling((n+1)/2)  + a(ceiling(n/2)) + a(floor(n/2)) with a(1) = 0, a(2) = 4 and a(3) = 8.

A067700.name: a(n) = 2*(n^2)!*Product_{k=0..n-1} k!/(n+k)!.
formula: a(n) = 2*(n^2)!*BarnesG(n+1)^2/BarnesG(2*n+1), where BarnesG(n) = A000178(n). - _G. C. Greubel_, May 04 2021

A067701.name: Numbers n such that phi(n-1) + phi(n+1) = phi(2n).

A067702.name: Numbers k such that sigma(k) == 0 (mod k+2).

A067703.name: Terms in the decimal expansion of 1/(7*5^n) before the block of decimals 142857 (the period of 1/7) appears.

A067710.name: n! sum{k|n} (sum{j=1 to k} 1/j); the k-sum is over the positive divisors, k, of n.

A067711.name: a(n+1) is the smallest square > a(n) such that the digits of a(n) are all (with multiplicity) properly contained in the digits of a(n+1), with a(0)=1.

A067712.name: Numbers n such that sum of exponents in prime factorization of n is > log(n).
formula: OMEGA(n) > log(n), where OMEGA is the total number of prime factors.

A067713.name: a(n+1) is the smallest square > a(n) such that the digits of a(n) are all (with multiplicity) contained in the digits of a(n+1), with a(0)=1.

A067714.name: a(n+1) is the smallest square > a(n) such that the digits of a(n) are all (with multiplicity) properly contained in the digits of a(n+1), with a(0)=4.

A067715.name: Sum of exponents in prime factorization of n is < log(n).

A067716.name: The least number k whose standard deviation of its prime factors (rounded up if necessary), with each factor counted according to its frequency of occurrence in the prime factorization of k (A067631) is n.

A067717.name: a(n+1) is the smallest square > a(n) such that the digits of a(n) are all (with multiplicity) contained in the digits of a(n+1), with a(0)=4.

A067718.name: Numbers k such that sigma(2^k+1) == 0 (mod k).

A067719.name: Numbers k such that sigma(k^2 + 1) == 0 (mod k).

A067720.name: Numbers k such that phi(k^2+1) = k*phi(k+1).

A067721.name: Least number k such that k (k + n) is a perfect square, or 0 if impossible.

A067722.name: Least positive integer k such that n*(n + k) is a perfect square.

A067723.name: Nontrivial palindromes k such that phi(k) is also a palindrome.

A067725.name: a(n) = 3*n^2 + 6*n.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + 6*n + 3, with n>0, a(0)=0. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 08 2010

A067728.name: a(n) = 2*n^2 + 8*n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{j=4..n} (j - k), n >= 4. - _Zerinvary Lajos_, May 11 2007

A067729.name: Numbers k such that floor(log(3)^k) is prime.

A067730.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n-1) + sigma(n+1) = sigma(2n).

A067731.name: Maximum number of distinct parts in a self-conjugate partition of n, or 0 if n=2.
formula: a(n) = r - (s mod 2), where n = r(r+1)/2 + s with 0 <= s <= r; i.e. r = floor((sqrt(8n+1)-1)/2).

A067732.name: Numbers k such that phi(prime(k) + 1) == 0 (mod k).

A067733.name: Numbers k such that phi(prime(k)-1) == 0 (mod k).

A067734.name: Number of ways writing n as a product of decimal digits of some other number which has no digits equal to 1.
formula: a(A002473(n)) > 0 for n > 1. - _David A. Corneth_, Jun 14 2017

A067735.name: Number of partitions of 2^n into distinct parts.

A067737.name: Integers n such that [number of integers k such that k is not of the form m + reverse(m) for any m and n occurs in the "Reverse and Add!" trajectory of k] is greater than [number of integers k such that n = k + reverse(k)].

A067738.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n)+sigma(sigma(n)) is prime.

A067739.name: Integers x such that for some integer y we have uphi(x) = uphi(y) = x-y, where uphi(n) = A047994(n) is the unitary totient function: If n = Product p_i^e_i, uphi(n) = Product (p_i^e_i - 1).

A067740.name: Smallest number k such that sigma(k)/sigma(phi(k)) = n.

A067741.name: Integers y such that for some integer x we have uphi(x) = uphi(y) = x-y, where uphi(n) = A047994(n) is the unitary totient function: If n = Product p_i^e_i, uphi(n) = Product (p_i^e_i - 1).

A067742.name: Number of middle divisors of n, i.e., divisors in the half-open interval [sqrt(n/2), sqrt(n*2)).
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} (-1)^(k-1)*x^(k*(k+1)/2)/(1-x^k). (This g.f. corresponds to the assertion in Theorem 2.)
Another g.f., corresponding to the definition: Sum_{k>=1} x^(2*k*(k+1))*(1-x^(6*k^2))/(1-x^(2*k)) +  Sum_{k>=0} x^((k+1)*(2*k+1))*(1-x^((2*k+1)*(3*k+2))/(1-x^(2*k+1). - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jan 04 2021
a(A128605(n)) = n and a(m) <> n for m < A128605(n). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Mar 14 2007
It appears that a(n) = A240542(n) - A240542(n-1), the difference between two adjacent Dyck paths as defined in A237593. - _Hartmut F. W. Hoft_, Feb 06 2017
The above conjecture is essentially the same as _Michel Marcus_'s conjecture in A237593. - Omar E. Pol, Dec 20 2020

A067743.name: Number of divisors of n not in the half-open interval [sqrt(n/2), sqrt(n*2)).

A067744.name: Number of terms yielding particularly small errors in a numerical integration of exp((cos(x)-1)/(cos(x)+1)) having non-monotonic sub-geometric convergence.

A067745.name: Numerator of ((3*n - 2)/(n^(2*n - 1)*(2*n - 1)*4^(n - 1))).
formula: Assuming the above conjecture, a(n) = a((8+(3*n-2)*4^k)/12), for all k >= 1. - _L. Edson Jeffery_, Feb 15 2015

A067747.name: Primes interleaved between composite numbers: n-th prime followed by the n-th composite number.
formula: a(2*n-1) = A000040(n); a(2*n) = A002808(n). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 29 2014
a(n) = A000040(ceiling(n/2))*A000035(n) + A002808(ceiling(n/2))*A059841(n), equivalent to the Zumkeller formula. - _Chayim Lowen_, Jul 29 2015

A067748.name: Smallest member of the first occurrence of exactly n consecutive primes whose sum of digits is also prime, or 0 if no such set of primes exists.

A067749.name: Numbers k such that k and 3^k end with the same two digits.

A067750.name: Numbers k whose last digit is the k-th digit of Pi.

A067751.name: Number of solutions in nonnegative integers of xy+xz+yz=n.

A067752.name: Number of unordered solutions of xy + xz + yz = n in nonnegative integers.

A067753.name: Number of primitive solutions in nonnegative integers of xy+xz+yz=n.

A067754.name: Number of unordered primitive solutions to xy+xz+yz=n.

A067755.name: Even legs of Pythagorean triangles whose other leg and hypotenuse are both prime.

A067756.name: Prime hypotenuses of Pythagorean triangles with a prime leg.

A067757.name: Numbers k whose last digit is the k-th digit of sqrt(2).

A067758.name: Numbers k such that sigma(prime(k) - 1) == 0 (mod k).

A067759.name: Numbers k such that sigma(prime(k) + 1) == 0 (mod k).

A067760.name: a(n) = least positive k such that (2n+1)+2^k is prime, or 0 if no such k exists.

A067761.name: Positive integers divisible by 5 but not by 7.

A067763.name: Square array read by antidiagonals of base n numbers written as 122...222 with k 2's (and a suitable interpretation for n=0, 1 or 2).

A067764.name: Numerators of the coefficients in exp(x/(1-x)) power series.
formula: a(n) is the numerator of Sum_{i=1..n} binomial(n-1, i-1)/i!.
a(n) is also the numerator of (Sum_{m>=0} binomial(n+m-1,n)/m!)/e, with A067653(n) as the denominator. See as example A000332 = binomial(n,4) below. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Dec 26 2013
a(n) = numerator(hypergeom([1 - n], [2], -1)) for n > 0. - _Peter Luschny_, Feb 02 2019

A067765.name: Order of linear Heyting semi-lattice on n points.
formula: a(0)=1; for n>0, a(n) = product((1+a(r))^binomial(n, r), r=0..n-1).

A067766.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n)^2>4*sigma_2(n) where sigma_2(n) is the sum of squares over the divisors of n.

A067767.name: Number of alternating link diagrams with n crossings, 2 connected components and two external legs.

A067768.name: Number of alternating link diagrams with n crossings, 3 connected components and two external legs.

A067769.name: Number of tiling variants for polyominoes with n cells.

A067771.name: Number of vertices in Sierpiński triangle of order n.

A067772.name: One half of the number of non-self-conjugate balanced partitions.

A067773.name: a(n) is the unique positive integer m which has a self-conjugate partition whose parts are the first n primes.
formula: a(n) = 2 prime(n) + Sum_{i=1..n-1} prime(n-i)*(prime(i+1)-prime(i)) = A014342(n-1) - A014342(n-2).

A067774.name: Primes p such that p+2 is not a prime.
formula: a(n) ~ n log n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jul 01 2013

A067775.name: Primes p such that p + 4 is composite.
formula: a(n) ~ n log n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Nov 22 2013

A067776.name: Numbers k such that binomial(2*k,k) * B(2*k) is an integer where B(k) are the Bernoulli numbers B(1)=-1/2 B(2)=1/6 B(4)=-1/30... B(2*m+1)=0 m>1.

A067777.name: Numbers k such that (2*k)! * B(6*k) is an integer where B(k) are the Bernoulli numbers B(1)=-1/2 B(2)=1/6 B(4)=-1/30... B(2*m+1)=0 m>1.

A067778.name: Numbers n such that gcd(n, numerator(B(2n)) is not squarefree where B(2n) are the Bernoulli numbers.

A067779.name: Primes such that the sum of the squares of its digits is equal to the product of its digits.

A067780.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n)/phi(n) is prime.

A067781.name: Numbers n such that phi(n) and sigma(n) are simultaneously perfect squares.
formula: A067781 = A006532 intersect A039770. [From _M. F. Hasler_, Sep 22 2009]

A067782.name: Minimal delay time for an n-element sorting network.

A067783.name: Numbers k such that prime(k+1)^2 == prime(k)^2 (mod k).

A067784.name: Numbers k such that prime(k+1)^4 == prime(k)^4 (mod k).

A067785.name: Numbers k such that prime(k)^3 == prime(k+1)^3 (mod k).

A067786.name: Numbers n such that phi(n) = 2*pi(n) where pi(n) = A000720(n) and phi(n) = A000010(n).

A067787.name: Numbers n such that the number of primes not exceeding sigma(n) equals phi(n), i.e., pi(sigma(n)) = phi(n).

A067788.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) - phi(n) = pi(n).

A067789.name: Numbers k whose last digit is the k-th digit of log(2).

A067790.name: Numbers n such that n and prime(n) end with the same digit.
formula: It seems that a(n) is asymptotic to 10n and that a(n) = 10n + O(sqrt(n)) (i.e. (a(n) - 10n)/sqrt(n) is bounded).

A067791.name: Smallest multidigit prime such that the sum of the squares of its digits is equal to n times the product of its digits, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A067792.name: a(n) is the least prime >= sigma(n).

A067795.name: Numbers n such that 2*n+1 is the next prime after sigma(n).

A067797.name: Numbers n such that phi(n)+phi(n+1) = n+2.

A067800.name: Nonprime n such that phi(n) > n/2.

A067804.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of walks (each step +/-1) of length 2n which have a cumulative value of 0 last at step 2k.
formula: O.g.f. A(x,y) = 1 + x*d/dx(log(B(x,y))), where B(x,y) is the o.g.f. of A120406. - _Peter Bala_, Jul 17 2015

A067805.name: Numbers n such that the area of the parallelogram formed by the vectors (n, prime(n)) and (n+1, prime(n+1)) is an integer square, i.e., Det[{{n, prime(n)},{n+1, prime(n+1)}}] is an integer square.

A067809.name: Composite n such that sigma(3*n) < prime(n).

A067810.name: Composite n such that sigma(2*n) < prime(n).

A067811.name: Numbers n such that phi(n)^2 + sigma(n)^2 is an integer square.

A067812.name: Nonprime n such that 2n+1 is prime.

A067813.name: Start of a record-breaking run of consecutive integers with a number of prime factors (counted with multiplicity) equal to 3.

A067814.name: The start of a record-breaking run of consecutive integers with a number of prime factors (counted with multiplicity) equal to 4.

A067816.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n+1) - sigma(n) = n + 1.

A067817.name: a(n) = Sum_{r|n, s|n, t|n, r<s<t} r*s*t.

A067818.name: Start with 1. To get a(n+1), describe a(n) in terms of the number of 0's, 1's, 2's,...,9's it has. Do not ignore leading 0's in the computation, but ignore them when listing the terms.

A067819.name: Sum of the divisors of binomial(2n,n).

A067820.name: The start of a record-breaking run of consecutive integers with a number of prime factors (counted with multiplicity) equal to 5.

A067821.name: The start of a record-breaking run of consecutive integers with a number of prime factors (counted with multiplicity) equal to 6.

A067822.name: The start of a record-breaking run of consecutive integers with a number of prime factors equal to 7.

A067823.name: Start with 2 and concatenate ("absorb") the next prime; continually repeat this procedure.

A067824.name: a(1) = 1; for n > 1, a(n) = 1 + Sum_{0 < d < n, d|n} a(d).
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s) / (2 - zeta(s)). - _Álvar Ibeas_, Dec 30 2018
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = x/(1 - x) + Sum_{k>=2} A(x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 18 2019

A067825.name: Even values of n such that sigma(n + 1) > sigma(n).

A067827.name: Even numbers such that n/2 is composite and sigma(n+1)>sigma(n).

A067828.name: Odd numbers such that sigma(n+1) < sigma(n).

A067829.name: Primes p such that sigma(p-2) < p.

A067830.name: Primes p such that sigma(p-4) < p.

A067831.name: Primes p such that sigma(p-6) < p.

A067832.name: Primes p such that sigma(p-6) > p.

A067833.name: Primes p such that sigma(p-4) > p.

A067834.name: Norm in ring Z[sqrt(3)] of (((-1+sqrt(3))^n)-1) is prime
formula: (-2)^n-lucasV(-2, -2, n)+1, where lucasV(-2, -2, n) is the solution of the recurrence relation v[0]=2, v[1]=-2, v[n+2]=-2*v[n+1]+2*v[n] n >= 0.

A067835.name: Average order of an element in the symmetric group S_n rounded down.

A067836.name: Let a(1)=2, f(n)=a(1)*a(2)*...*a(n-1) for n>=1 and a(n)=nextprime(f(n)+1)-f(n) for n>=2, where nextprime(x) is the smallest prime > x.

A067837.name: a(1)=2; to form a(n+1), append P, the largest prime < a(n), if any and Q, the smallest prime > a(n), at the beginning and the end of a(n), respectively.

A067838.name: Numbers n such that n and prime(n) end with the same two digits.

A067840.name: Factorial expansion of e^2 : exp(2)=sum n=1 to infinity a(n)/n!.

A067841.name: Numbers n such that n and prime(n) end with the same three digits.

A067844.name: Numbers k such that k and 2^k end with the same digit.

A067846.name: Least m such that A067513(m) = n.

A067847.name: Number of divisors d of n! such that d+1 is prime.

A067849.name: a(n) = max{k: f(n),...,f^k(n) are prime}, where f(m) = 2m+1 and f^k denotes composition of f with itself k times.

A067850.name: Highest power of 2 not exceeding n!.

A067852.name: Numbers n such that n divides prime(n^2)-1.

A067853.name: Numbers n such that n divides prime(n^2)+1.

A067854.name: a(n) = cardinality of the (ordered) list L_n defined inductively by: L_1 = {2}; if, reading from left to right, there is a member p of L_n such that prime(n+1) can be appended to the beginning or end of p so that their neighboring digits are equal, then append prime(n+1) to the beginning or end of p to obtain L_(n+1); otherwise, add prime(n+1) to the end of the list L_n to obtain L_(n+1).

A067855.name: Square of the Euclidean length of the vector of Littlewood-Richardson coefficients of Sum_{lambda |- n} s_lambda^2, where s_lambda are the symmetric Schur functions and the sum runs over all partitions lambda of n.
formula: Euler transform of A001868(n)/2. a(n) = Sum_{pi} Product_{m=1..n} binomial(2*p(m), p(m)), where pi runs through all nonnegative solutions of p(1) + 2*p(2) + ... + n*p(n)=n. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 25 2006
a(n) ~ 2^(2*n) / sqrt(c*Pi*n), where c = QPochhammer[1/4] = 0.688537537120339... - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Apr 22 2018

By definition, a(n) = Sum_{mu |- 2n} c_mu^2 where Sum_{lambda |- n} s_lambda^2 = Sum_{mu |- 2n} c_mu s_mu, where s_lambda are the Schur polynomials (symmetric in 2n variables) and the sums run over all partitions of n resp. 2n. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 19 2020

A067856.name: Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)/n^s = 1/(Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n + 1)/n^s).
formula: a(1) = 1 and a(n) = Sum{k | n, 1 < k} (-1)^k a(n/k) for n >= 2; the sum is over the divisors, k, of n, where k > 1. If n is odd, a(n) = mu(n), where mu(.) is the Moebius function. If n is even, a(n) = mu(m)* 2^(k-1), where n = m*2^k, m is odd integer, and k is a positive integer.
Sum_{n > 0} a(n)*x^n/(1 + x^n) = x. Moebius transform of A048298. Multiplicative with a(2^e) = 2^(e - 1), a(p) = -1 for p > 2, a(p^e) = 0 for p > 2 and e > 1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jan 02 2003
Sum_{n > 0} a(n)*log(1 + x^n)/n = x. - _Paul D. Hanna_, May 06 2003
a(n) = 0 if and only if n is divisible by the square of an odd prime (A038838). - _Michael Somos_, Aug 22 2006
1 = Sum_{k=1..n} a(k)*g(n/k), where g(x) = floor(x) - 2*floor(x/2). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Nov 11 2010
Dirichlet g.f.: 1/( zeta(s) * (1 - 2^(1-s)) ). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 02 2011
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = x + A(x^2) - A(x^3) + A(x^4) - A(x^5) + ... - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 11 2019

A067857.name: Sum_{k|n} a(k)/k! = Sum_{j=1 to n} 1/j, sum on left is over positive divisors k of n.
formula: MOBIUS transform of Harmonic Numbers is a(n)/n!. - _Michael Somos_, May 24 2015
a(n) = n! * Sum_{k=1..n} A191898(n,k)/k. - _Mats Granvik_, Jul 10 2016

A067858.name: J_n(n), where J is the Jordan function, J_n(n) = n^n product{p|n}(1 - 1/p^n), the product is over the distinct primes, p, dividing n.
formula: J_n(n) = sum{k|n} mu(n/k) k^n, where mu() is the Moebius function.

A067860.name: n is prime and the concatenation of numbers n_1, n_2, n_3, in that order, with n_1 + n_2 = n_3 (leading zeros are forbidden for nonzero n_i).

A067861.name: n is prime and is the concatenation of numbers n_1, n_2, n_3, in that order, with n_1 - n_2 = n_3. (Do not allow leading zeros for nonzero n_i.)

formula: a(n) = 20*(n-1)-a(n-1) for n>1, a(1)=7. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 08 2010

A067871.name: Number of primes between consecutive prime powers.

A067872.name: Least m>0 for which m*n^2 + 1 is a square.
formula: For n a power of an odd prime, a(n)=n^2-2. For n twice a power of an odd prime, a(n)=(n/2)^2-1. - T. D. Noe, Sep 13 2007

A067873.name: Numbers x satisfying x^2 - D*y^2 = 1 for more than one value of D distinct from x^2 - 1.

A067875.name: One player's total legal chess moves by piece type on standard chessboard.
formula: a(6) = a(4) + a(5) (Queen moves equal sum of Bishop and Rook moves). Generalizing all terms for n X n chessboards other than 8 x 8 requires defining how many pieces and how many types of pieces are originally on the board and/or can be promoted to, especially because of the way captures are counted.

A067881.name: Factorial expansion of sqrt(3) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)/n!.

A067882.name: Factorial expansion of log(2) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)/n!.

A067885.name: Product of 6 distinct primes.
formula: a(n) = n(log log n)^5/(120 log n). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Sep 14 2015

A067886.name: Numbers k such that 2^k+1 and 2^k-1 have the same number of distinct prime factors.

A067888.name: Numbers n such that tau(n+1)=tau(n-1) where tau(k)=A000005(k).

A067889.name: Primes sandwiched between two numbers having same number of divisors.

A067896.name: Trajectory of 41 under map x -> x/2 if x even, x-> 3x+3 if x odd.

A067897.name: a(n) = A000085(n) - (1 + Sum_{j=1..n-1} A000085(j)).
formula: a(n) = A000085(n) - A245176(n-1). - _Jon E. Schoenfield_, Mar 14 2021

A067898.name: Least digit not used in n (or 10 if n is pandigital).

A067899.name: Fractal palindromic primes of second order.

A067900.name: a(n) = 14*a(n-1) - a(n-2); a(0) = 0, a(1) = 8.
formula: a(n) = ( (7+4*sqrt(3))^n - (7-4*sqrt(3))^n )/sqrt(3), with n>=0. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Oct 02 2008

A067901.name: Numbers k such that floor(log(Pi)^k) is prime.

A067902.name: a(n) = 14*a(n-1) - a(n-2); a(0) = 2, a(1) = 14.
formula: a(n) = p^n + q^n, where p = 7 + 4*sqrt(3) and q = 7 - 4*sqrt(3). - _Tanya Khovanova_, Feb 06 2007

Let F(x) = Product_{n >= 0} (1 + x^(4*n+1))/(1 + x^(4*n+3)). Let alpha = 7 - 4*sqrt(3). This sequence gives the partial denominators in the simple continued fraction expansion of 1 + F(alpha) = 2.07140228197873197080... = 2 + 1/(14 + 1/(194 + 1/(2702 + ...))). Cf. A005248.

A067912.name: Engel expansion of zeta(4) = Pi^4/90 = Sum_{i>0} 1/i^4.

A067948.name: Triangle of labeled rooted trees according to the number of increasing edges.
formula: T(n, k) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} T(n, k) x^k = Product_{i=1..n-1} (n - i + i*x).
E.g.f.: Compositional inverse of (exp(x) - exp(x*t))/((1 - t)*exp(x*(1 + t))) = x + (1 + t)*x^2/2! + (2 + 5*t + 2*t^2)*x^3/3! + ...

Let f(x,t) = (1 - t)/(exp(-x) - t*exp(-x*t)) and let D be the operator f(x,t)*d/dx. Then the (n+1)-th row generating polynomial equals (D^n)(f(x,t)) evaluated at x = 0. See [Drake, example 1.7.2] for the combinatorial interpretation of this table in terms of labeled trees. (End)

A067955.name: Number of dissections of a convex polygon by nonintersecting diagonals into polygons with even number of sides and having a total number of n edges (sides and diagonals).

G.f. G(z) satisfies (1+z)*G^3 - z*G^2 - G + z = 0.

A067962.name: a(n) = F(n+2)*(Product_{i=1..n+1} F(i))^2 where F(i)=A000045(i) is the i-th Fibonacci number.
formula: a(n) = (F(3) * F(4) * ... * F(n+1))^2 * F(n+2), where F(n) = A000045(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.
a(n) is asymptotic to C^2*((1+sqrt(5))/2)^((n+2)^2)/(5^(n+3/2)) where C=1.226742010720353244... is the Fibonacci Factorial Constant, see A062073. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 28 2011
a(n) = a(n-1) * A001654(n+1), n > 0. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Sep 24 2015
